superEntry.entry:
R. Q. 1 cabocabN c
R. Q. 1. cabocabN, (T,) inf. n. cabocabapN, (K,) He defended his neighbours and family. (T, K.) [See also 1.] ＝ -A2- And He annoyed, molested, harmed, or hurt, (T, K,) people. (K.) ＝ -A3- And He made a thing to dangle, or move to and fro;
(L;) and made it to be in a state of motion, commotion, or agitation. (L, K. *) ― -b2- [Hence,] cabocabahu, inf. n. as above, (assumed tropical:) He left him, or made him to be, confounded, or perplexed, not knowing his right course; wavering, vacillating, or going to and fro. (Msb.) ＝ -A4- cabocabapN also signifies The dangling, or moving to and fro, of a thing suspended in the air: (S, M:) and tacabocubN↓ the being in a state of motion or commotion: (S, L:) [or the latter has both these meanings; for] you say, AlXRaIoCu tacabocaba↓ the thing dangled, or moved to and fro, (M, A, L,) in the air; (A;) and was in a state of commotion or agitation. (M, L.) It is said in a trad., fakaOanRiIOanoZuru UilaI yadayohi tucabocibaAni, meaning And it was as though I looked at his two sleeves in a state of commotion, or shaking. (TA.) And you say, bayona Oamorayoni tcabocaba↓ (assumed tropical:) He wavered, or vacillated, between two affairs. (MA.) And Oamoruhumo tacabocaba↓ (assumed tropical:) [Their state of affairs was, or became, fluctuating, or unsteady]. (Lh, T in art. dl.)
